Every time a dog has started howling and crying at night in summer, an old relative living in that house has passed away the following winter. If in August your dog starts whining, making sounds at midnight, maybe good idea to take care of a grandparent, uncle, etc. living there.

This has always happened with large dogs living outside in the backyard/garden doghouse, pit bulls, mutts. Not sure if an apartment chihuahua type meme dog can notice it. Probably related somehow to the stars and moon, sensing the seasons change, night sky, winds, night air, etc.

If you take a cold bath and wrap yourself in warm blankets afterwards, but are not sweating enough, as you should, you must tell your nurse to get into the bed with you, so her body heat warms you up too and helps you to start sweating well. 17th century English medicine trick.
Basically every time someone asks: "Is there a term for X?", the proper term that they are looking for is "being a fool".

Basically all 17th century Englishmen report that they sweat a lot and get heated after exiting a cold bath. They had good metabolism. Dr. Peat said a cold shower either speeds your metabolism a bit if you're healthy or tanks your body temperature down horrendously if hypothyroid

Or like it's written in Anatomy of Melancholy that a melancholic man might be made more melancholic by things that paradoxically turn other men less melancholic. The slower you walk, the more you stumble over rocks on the path. Cold baths as pagan gods either take or give a life.

17th century clinical case of an old fisherman, who lived to 106, burly and stout, eating mostly "brown bread and cheese", drinking "mild, clear beer". Perfect health until 104, when his boat sank in the river in an accident, and he soon developed bladder issues from the stress.

You often see this pattern of disease appearing after some accident. Old people fall, break a bone, can't get up, soon develop dementia. Skin issues after a car crash. Any high acute stress unlocks lurking disease. If a catastrophe is survived easy, one still needs a lot of rest.

Another fisherman there lived to 103, bathed in the cold water of the river often, slept in his boat in the cool night air, being gently rocked by the river like in a cradle. Says one must not sleep too long to live a long life. All of them hauled fish nets, strong forearms, grip

It's weird that we look at cold water as an anti-horny thing today, e.g. "go take a cold shower, bro", but in 17th century England it was seen as a libido stimulant, bathing in cold winter water was an erectile dysfunction cure, cold baths made people insanely horny afterwards...
